[2026-05-05 glm-5.1] Python over Rust/Go for substrate implementation
Reasoning: The spec's deployment model is "library, in-process." Agents are Python and import substrate directly. Rust or Go would force a sidecar (HTTP/gRPC layer) on day one, which the spec explicitly defers to Phase 3. At homelab scale (≤50 agents, ≤10k work-items), Postgres is doing all the real work — the library is orchestrating SQL calls and signing bytes. Performance margin from a systems language is irrelevant. Python buys native agent integration and implementation velocity that matters.
Alternatives considered: Rust (compile-time safety on concurrency contract, but sidecar forced immediately), Go (good Postgres story via pgx, but same sidecar problem, less ergonomic domain modeling than Python)
Constraints: Must be importable by Python agents; must run in-process; no HTTP server in MVP
----------------------------------------
[2026-05-05 glm-5.1] Schema-per-project over DB-per-project isolation
Reasoning: User proposed this mid-design. DB-per-project (the spec's original design) multiplies connection pools (10 projects × 5 idle connections = 50 idle connections), requires per-DB pg_dump, and forces postgres_fdw or app-level fan-out for federated reads. Schema-per-project gives the same engine-enforced isolation (GRANT ON SCHEMA is checked by the same code path as GRANT ON DATABASE), one pool, one backup target, and federation reads are a GRANT SELECT away. The spec's BR-13 already concedes DB-per-project needs migration at scale — schema-per-project IS that migration, arrived at from a better direction.
Alternatives considered: DB-per-project (spec original — connection multiplication, operational tax), tenant_id + RLS (future option — schema-per-project is stricter isolation with less overhead)
Constraints: Public API surface must be unchanged (§19); Substrate handle still owns one logical project namespace; cross-project links still forbidden by construction
----------------------------------------
[2026-05-05 glm-5.1] SET LOCAL search_path per transaction for schema scoping
Reasoning: Each project's tables live in a dedicated schema. Rather than qualifying every table name in every SQL statement (fragile, verbose), SET LOCAL search_path at transaction start scopes all unqualified names to the project schema. SET LOCAL auto-resets at commit/rollback, so connections returned to the pool are clean — no risk of cross-project contamination. This works because all substrate operations are transactional (reads use transactions too via mgr.transaction()).
Alternatives considered: Fully qualified table names (fragile, couples SQL to schema name), SET search_path with manual reset (risk of stale search_path on pool return), autocommit mode (loses transaction control)
Constraints: Must not leak search_path between projects; must work with psycopg3's pool + transaction() context manager; synchronous_commit=on must also be set per session
----------------------------------------
[2026-05-05 glm-5.1] psycopg3 sync with dict_row over asyncpg
Reasoning: Substrate is a library, not a daemon. Agents call it synchronously. asyncpg would force async/await through the entire call stack with no performance benefit at homelab scale. psycopg3 (v3) is modern, actively maintained, supports SELECT FOR UPDATE naturally, and its pool (psycopg-pool) handles connection lifecycle cleanly. dict_row factory gives dict-style access to query results which is cleaner than tuple indexing for the projection update code.
Alternatives considered: asyncpg (async not needed for library mode, would complicate caller API), SQLAlchemy (too heavy for what's needed, ORM leaks across API boundary), raw libpq (too low-level)
Constraints: Must support SELECT FOR UPDATE, connection pooling, row_factory customization, and transaction context managers
----------------------------------------
[2026-05-05 glm-5.1] Custom migration runner over Alembic
Reasoning: Substrate manages its own schema (7 tables, indexes, constraints). The migration needs are simple: numbered SQL files applied in order. Alembic brings autogenerate complexity and ORM coupling that's unnecessary. The custom runner creates the tracking table on first run (CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS), discovers .sql files from the migrations/ directory, and applies pending ones in order within a transaction. Simple, auditable, no external dependencies.
Alternatives considered: Alembic (ORM-coupled, over-engineered for 7 tables), Django migrations (framework-coupled), no migrations/inline DDL (no audit trail, no version tracking)
Constraints: Must be idempotent, must bootstrap tracking table on first run, must handle schema-per-project (migrations run per-schema)
----------------------------------------
[2026-05-05 glm-5.1] transition() as high-level API combining FR-11/12 + event append + claim release
Reasoning: The spec lists FR-11 (validate transition) as a separate operation, but in practice every state transition requires validation AND event append AND projection update AND claim release (FR-08: "successful state transitions release implicitly"). Making the caller orchestrate these steps would be error-prone and violate the "protocol, not Postgres connection" API principle. The transition() method on Substrate handles the full flow: load pinned workflow, validate transition exists, validate role, sign, allocate seq, insert event, update projection, release claim — all in one transaction.
Alternatives considered: Expose append_event as the only mutation API (forces caller to do validation), separate validate() + execute() calls (two round-trips, TOCTOU risk), no claim auto-release on transition (violates FR-08)
Constraints: Must validate against pinned workflow version (not latest), must be atomic in one transaction, must reject pre-signed events
----------------------------------------
[2026-05-05 glm-5.1] Unknown transitions treated as no-ops in replay (not halted)
Reasoning: The replay code halts when it encounters a transition it can't resolve in the workflow definition. But append_event() allows any transition name (it's used for system events like "custom_event", "link_created", etc.). If replay halts on these, it reports false-positive halted items. The fix: if a transition isn't found in the workflow AND isn't one of the known system events, treat it as a non-state-changing no-op. Halted should be reserved for actual errors (revoked keys, missing workflow versions).
Alternatives considered: Strict halt on unknown transitions (false positives on system events), require all transitions in workflow def (breaks system events), maintain a whitelist of system transitions (fragile)
Constraints: Replay must not halt on legitimate system events; replay must halt on actual errors; replay must not corrupt the replay table
----------------------------------------
